final_thought: Standing on the new concrete seawall, watching massive container ships
  navigate by satellite, she wondered if the river still remembered the songs she
  and the Baiji once sang together in the language of currents and tides
last_days_scenario: The demolition notice came on the same day Chen heard the last
  traditional fishing boat had been replaced by an automated harvester. For fifty
  years, she had guided vessels through the Tongling bend where the Yangtze curved
  like a dragon's spine, reading the water the way her ancestors read the stars. Her
  grandfather had taught her to listen for the Baiji's clicks in the muddy water -
  'The river speaks through them,' he'd said. Now the constant drone of cargo ships,
  dredging equipment, and construction machinery made it impossible to hear anything
  but industrial noise. The New Yangtze Megaport Complex would pave over the stone
  pier where fifteen generations of her family had launched their boats. Like the
  Baiji, she had become an evolutionary dead end - a navigation system rendered obsolete
  by progress. The river that had sustained her people for millennia now carried only
  the mechanical heartbeat of global commerce, drowning out twenty million years of
  whispered wisdom in its concrete-channeled flow.
